&lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;no star rating&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I haven't read this series in a long, long time; it would be interesting to see how it holds up. (The first few reviews suggest: not well.) I remember the world-building more than anything; it had a very distict texture. It falls in my memory somewhere in the neighborhood of [b:Wolf Tower|293395|Wolf Tower (Claidi Journals, #1)|Tanith Lee|https://d.gr-assets.com/books/1391128560s/293395.jpg|1279335] and [b:The City of Ember|307791|The City of Ember (Book of Ember, #1)|Jeanne DuPrau|https://d.gr-assets.com/books/1397931596s/307791.jpg|2285229] and some other book that's on the tip of my tongue.&lt;/p&gt;</content><category term="2002"/><category term="f-c-mg-ya"/><category term="3-fmt-f-novel"/><category term="f-scifi-specfic"/></entry><entry><title>Wise Child (Doran, #1)</title><link href="https://tshynik.github.io/wise-child-doran-1.html" rel="alternate"/><published>2002-01-01T00:00:00-05:00</published><updated>2002-01-01T00:00:00-05:00</updated><author><name>Akiva</name></author><id>tag:tshynik.github.io,2002-01-01:/wise-child-doran-1.html</id><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class='writer'&gt;by Monica Furlong&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
